of you played Morrowind?</span><hr size=1> <br>
I like how they do armor in that game, and I think i might be a good suggestion for how it is done in EQ 2.<br>
<br>
Instead of putting a level restriction on the item, the AC of the armor should be reflected in some formula with the AC of the armor and the Characters skill in wearing that type of armor.<br>
<br>
So basically there would be an AC limit based on skill of the player.<br>
<br>
Examples of armor skill categories could be :<br>
<br>
Chain armors<br>
Splint armors<br>
Plate armors<br>
Dragon Scale armors<br>
Supernatural armors<br>
cloth armor/unarmored.<br>
<br>
Such skills would increase much like one's defense skill currently increases.  When you take hits on that type of armor you have some chance to increase in skill.<br>
<br>
The nice thing about Morrowind though is anyone can wear any type of armor.  So you have &quot;battlemages&quot;  Casters wearing plate armor.<br>
<br>
Though the heavier the armor the more str required, and since a caster is likely to put skill points into int, or mana based stats instead of strength, a caster with plate armor should not be so popular, etc.<br>
<br>
<br>
I also think there should be more interactive/dynamic quests which do not require grinding as much as solving puzzles, and the result of which may be permanent increases to skill or stats instead of items.<br>
<br>
The dynamic part of it may be specific puzzles which require one to think or used a specific strategy, or require a specific item which may vary from player to player.<br>
<br>
I am not suggesting it would be unique to any one player, but it could vary enough that one going into the quest won't just be able to have some print out of someone elses walk through, because they will likely have the dynamic parts different for them.  Perhaps each dynamic part may have 5 variations, or 10 , though have it some unknown amount so one can not just walk up there knowing for certain they can complete the quest with someone elses walkthrough.<br>
<br>
And restarting the quest woouldnt reset the dynamic parts...there would be a flag on each character (hidden flag of course) so that the game knows what dynamic part you have encountered of that quest.  To prevent someone from trying to restart the quest to do it over a possibly easier way.<br>
<br>
And once such a quest is completed adding a flag to that character which would prevent them from triggering that quest again.  The flag could much be like the keys on the key ring, but instead a notch on ones belt....<br>
<br>
<br>
Anyway, the system of MMORPG can definately be made better.  I am hoping EQ is not the standard but will be just the beginning of the possibilities for future MMORPG's.<br>
<br>
I have hope. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubanegrivm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Banegrivm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 511<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/02 4:44:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1619.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Have any of you played Morrowind?</span><hr size=1> Really some very cool thoughts and ideas. One of the things that I always thought you could do if you made everything no drop was to allow tradeskills make better things that might rival or be just as good as the dropped items.<br>
