<br>
Let's suppose I want to do a quest (which I frequently do because they are interesting).<br>
<br>
Firstly, I have to find a quest. This means running around hailing random NPCs and then persuing the quest in the hope that it will be suitable for my level and class (which is pretty damned unlikely) or a;ternatively I have to go to a spoiler site to search for a suitable quest... And as soon as you visit a spoiler quest, the quest is spoiled =) [N.B. this may be something that they willl address with PoP looking a the patch messages]<br>
<br>
Secondly, you have to go through the dialogue. So many dialogues are ridiculously difficult to work through. It isn't a fun challenge working out how the designers spelt a particular word. The way to bypass this tedious item is to... you guessed it... go to a spoiler site. [N.B. they've partially fixed this with Luclin, since they have been more careful with the dialogue there]<br>
<br>
Thirdly, so you have to deliver a note to so and so who is somewhere in Freeport. Do you want to spend hours running around that maze trying to find the person? Nope. Spoiler site. [If you've ever done the citizenship quest in Shar Val, that's how finding someone for a quest should work]<br>
<br>
Fourthly, kill mob X. So frequently the monster either trivs, is impossible to find, has to be camped for hours upon hours, needs a raid force etc. etc. At this point you probabnly give up.<br>
<br>
Fifth, you complete the quest, and are rewarded hooray! With a tiny amount of experience and small leather sleeves. Hurroo. =(<br>
<br>
Quests should be shorter, easier (in the sense of not having to figure out dialogue spelling errors or camp a mob for four days) and more rewarding (i.e. actually a decent alternative to grinding . camping dropped items). Plus it would be cool if at certain points, quests branched out so that there were several endings =)<br>
