:shrugs <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bjond>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1281<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/23/02 11:18:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1619.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Hmm, as far as making everything no-drop ..</span><hr size=1> .. it was a qualified &quot;everything&quot;.  I mean everything that directly or indirectly requires you to slay something to obtain an item should result in a no-drop item.  I think tradeskills that result in tradable items should all ultimately be fashioned from vendor items or other sources that are inherently non-competitive.  Want to twink?  Go for it, but you can't use dropables.<br>
<br>
What would this odd mechanism accomplish?  Pretty much the only problem with twinks is when someone puts a claim in for an item for their twink versus people that are there for their mains.  Or, people that farm things for their twinks, preventing others from obtaining that gear for their main.  Making things no-drop prevents that kind of behavior.  It doesn't have many other effects.  It is VERY important to support twinking, but I think it's just as important to prevent folks from using a twink as a license for greed.<br>
<br>
IMHO, that isn't the biggest problem in EQ, though.  The single biggest problem in EQ today is competition over in-game resources.  If there are plenty of things to kill, everyone is happy.  If there are bottlenecks for &quot;must have&quot; items, people get in insane fights over it.  This is an issue of zone design and item distribution that drop or no-drop does not impact.  Zones with a respawn rate that scales can support more people of more varied skill levels (eg. Loio).  Zones with static spawn rates get clogged up (eg. Velks).  Zones with nice drops off specific static spawns encourgage camping.  Zones with distributed drops support both dungeon crawling and camping.<br>
<br>
EQ has pretty bad interzone balance.  There are a few really hot xp zones and a few really hot drop zones.  These aren't just a little better than other zones, they're phenominally better.  There are tons of zones that are completely empty.  Why?  Poor risk v. reward.  This is one that VI is well aware of, but they don't often address it.  Why not?  My guess is that whatever process they might have for zone creation and balancing, it's so archaic and onerous that it is very painful for them to balance the zones.  It's so painful that they seem to far prefer adding new zones to balancing existing ones. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=veldalina>Veldalina</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 64<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/24/02 3:05:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1619.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Item decay</span><hr size=1> Personally I don't like the whole item decay thing that's said to be in EQ2.  It was in DAoC, and honestly it was a pain.  When you get equipment, you want to be able to hand it down to guildies and stuff, which doesn't make a lot of sense if it's beat up to 20% decay (with the damage of the weapon or the armor class of the armor being negatively effected by this).<br>
<br>
I don't know what's fun about being the highest level in the game, having the best weapon in the game but having to farm <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>another</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> one after a few weeks of use because it decayed.<br>
<br>
The way it worked in DAoC was that items would color con like mobs, and if things were equal to your level or lower they'd decay slowly, but if they were above, they'd decay quickly.  So if you gave your level 1 fighter twink the best sword in the game, it not only wouldn't work that well, but it would also decay really fast and would soon be useless.  This did reduce twinking, but to be frank it was just not that much fun; better to just make a situation where characters get a disadvantage by using level-inappropriate items, but not ruining the items themselves.<br>
<br>
The worst part was when you'd level slowly (a few bad nights, taking extra deaths and losing experience - happens to all of us) and find that your level-appropriate equipment was decaying on you.  Generally stuff would decay when you'd get hit for armor or use the weapon to hit with, so melee characters even had it much worse than my cleric and caster characters did.<br>
<br>
Weapons and armor were just generally kind of boring in DAoC due to the level restrictions and such.  Getting equipment was not too exciting.  Whole sets of armor dropped fairly frequently.  They had to, because people had to get new equipment when levelling up and were always aware of what they should be wearing.  For my cleric, there was Duskwalker chain available in the level 18-24 dungeon, then a couple of different forgettable &quot;tiers&quot; of chain in the 30-45 dungeon.  There was not much of an economy, because usually if you hunted normally in the dungeon appropriate for your level, enough would drop for you to be completely outfitted in under a week.<br>
<br>
To discourage camping, items didn't often drop off of special mobs unless it was part of a quest, and when that did occur, the mob would usually spawn every 5 minutes anyway.  And quest items would always drop right into your inventory the first time you killed the mob involved, but they would not drop into the inventory of anyone that didn't specifically have that quest (and you could not repeat quests with the same character).<br>
<br>
Anyway, although the loot situation in EQ is sometimes a bit of a pain, it's at least not bland like DAoC's was.  I'd rather not see item decay and level restrictions on items. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yuvail>Yuvail</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Rosen Lord</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/24/02 5:38:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1619.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_supermad.gif" align=absmiddle>  HA</span><hr size=1> Jealous, hardly.  And I said nothing about me leaving because of twinks.  Twinks annoy me, because it just proves that you are so incompetent that you can't go from a naked level 1 warrior with your guild short sword to a level 30 warrior with validous and 2 ykeshas, without starting off with that at level 1.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bjond>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1284<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/24/02 6:41:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1619.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Hmm</span><hr size=1> My experience with twinks is that they are by far the best players in the game.  However, that's the self-twinked.  The &quot;ebay&quot; or &quot;gift&quot; twinks are almost worse than d00ds.  IMHO, they are a problem, but only when you support selling characters.  An idiot level 1 with SODs just survives a bit longer than the common idiot -- it's a self-correcting issue.<br>
<br>
It would be pretty easy to solve the game-play issues related to ebay.  Just have VI broker the transactions and force a name change before the sold char can log on.  Add a command like /charstatus that shows the number of times that character has been sold.  From what I've experienced, pretty much everyone detests the clueless ebays.  They'd be shunned.<br>
<br>
BTW, yes, I know you aren't leaving because of twinks.  That's generally true for most of those that consider themselves twink-haters.  That's my point.  It's why twink-haters need not be considered for game design.  They'll play anyway.  Twinkers are often ready to leave the game and twinking keeps them playing.  So, in order to make more money, support twinking. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=1619.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=1619.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1619.topic&index=12><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/classic/addReply.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.threadControl?topicID=1619.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1619.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=1619.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub94.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="firionaviefrm1">Firiona Vie General Chat<option value="firionaviefrm9">OT/OOC Forum<option value="firionaviefrm4">The Soapbox<option value="fi